# Supplementary Fig. 7 | a) NMR chemical shift titration of $[ 1 3 0 , 1 5 \mathsf { M } ]$ cCaM with 6-NBT.

Chemical shift perturbations $( \Delta \delta )$ of $\mathsf { H }$ (open symbols) and N (filled symbols) atoms of cCaM backbone amides K94 (circles), D95 (squares), V108 (triangles), V142 (diamonds), Q143 (hexagons), T146 (pentagons) and the sidechain amide of N111 (stars) were fitted globally to a 1:1 binding model with the shared $\mathsf { K } _ { \mathsf { d } }$ . The solid lines show the best fit with the $\mathsf { K } _ { \mathsf { d } }$ value of $1 . 0 \pm 0 . 1 \mathrm { \ m M }$ . b) NMR chemical shift titration of $[ 1 3 0 , 1 5 \mathsf { M } ]$ AlleyCat with 6-NBT Chemical shift perturbations $( \Delta \delta )$ of $\mathsf { H }$ (open symbols) and N (filled symbols) atoms of AlleyCat backbone amides F89 (squares), E92 (triangles), I100 (diamonds), H107 (stars), and the sidechain amide of N111 (circles) were fitted globally to a 1:1 binding model with the shared $\mathsf { K } _ { \mathsf { d } }$ . The solid lines show the best fit with the $\mathsf { K } _ { \mathsf { d } }$ value of $3 . 3 \pm 0 . 7$ mM. In both cases experiments were performed in $2 0 \mathsf { m M }$ HEPES pH 6.9, 100 mM NaCl, 10 mM CaCl2 at $2 9 8 \mathsf { K }$ .

